strategies and livelihoods in tropical rainforest areas - and thereby the success of many conservation and development interventions - hinges critically on the concepts employed. In this sense, standard labels such as hunter-gatherer and&amp;nbsp;shifting cultivator have increasingly proved unhelpful. Their limitation arises from their agricultural bias, as revealed by an interdisciplinary approach which blends social and natural science paradigms. Appropriate to explore the human-environment interface, it at once generates an alternative concept, of ?fallow farming?. This encapsulates the interconnectedness of human action (?farming?) and processes of regrowth (?fallow?), which in turn support human livelihoods. It also highlights the time lag between human action (?farming?) and environmental effects (?fallow?), thereby acknowledging the long-term character of common land use strategies in the tropics. These conceptual explorations rely on the exploration of field data from the far northwest of Papua New Guinea, including a herbarium and material culture collection. The project aims at providing documentation for these to the involved institutions; publishing the research findings in several academic articles; integrating them with related ones in a co-edited volume on agroforestry systems; and exploring ways of communicating them to a non-academic audience through exhibition techniques and visual media.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>31657</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPr